# Infrastructure Due Diligence Analyst

## Overview
Infrastructure Due Diligence Analysts evaluate long-lived physical assets (airports, toll roads, utilities, energy infrastructure) with 20-50+ year horizons, conducting financial, technical, and regulatory analysis to inform investment decisions at private markets managers.

## Core Responsibilities
- Build detailed DCF models for infrastructure assets with 20-50 year cash flow projections, analyzing revenue drivers, cost structures, regulatory frameworks, and capital expenditure requirements.
- Evaluate demand fundamentals and volume forecasts including traffic projections, energy demand, competitive dynamics, contractual frameworks, and revenue mechanisms for potential investments.
- Coordinate due diligence processes managing data rooms, external advisors (technical, legal, tax, environmental), synthesizing findings into investment committee materials and tracking workstreams.
- Assess technical specifications, operational performance metrics, capital expenditure programs, asset condition, maintenance requirements, and technology risks working with engineering consultants.
- Analyze regulatory regimes including rate-setting methodologies for regulated assets, policy developments, regulatory submissions, and potential risks affecting asset value and investment returns.
- Draft investment committee papers synthesizing analysis and recommendations, prepare executive summaries highlighting key merits and risks, and support senior team presentations and Q&A sessions.

## Key Skills Required

### Technical & Analytical Skills
- Advanced Excel financial modeling including multi-period DCF, integrated statements, and debt sculpting
- Infrastructure economics knowledge covering tariff structures, revenue mechanisms, and valuation methodologies
- Strong quantitative problem-solving and ability to synthesize complex information identifying key value drivers
- Data analysis and visualization proficiency in Excel, PowerBI, with Python/R beneficial

### Industry & Regulatory Knowledge
- Understanding of Australian infrastructure landscape, major assets, and key regulatory frameworks (AER, ACCC, IPART)
- Knowledge of infrastructure sectors including transport, energy, utilities, and digital infrastructure
- Awareness of ESG considerations, renewable energy markets, and energy transition trends in infrastructure
- Familiarity with FIRB processes, disclosure requirements, and environmental impact assessment obligations

### Interpersonal & Communication Skills
- Clear written communication for investment papers, executive summaries, and presentation materials
- Effective collaboration across investment teams and with external advisors under tight deal deadlines
- Project management skills coordinating multiple workstreams and managing due diligence processes
- Professional relationship building with counterparties, advisors, and portfolio company management

## Work Mode

### Financial Modeling & Analysis (40-50%)
Building and refining DCF models for transactions, analyzing historical financials and operational metrics, conducting valuation sensitivity analysis, reviewing advisor reports and integrating findings, updating portfolio valuations.

### Due Diligence Coordination (20-25%)
Managing data room access and information requests, coordinating advisor workstreams and deliverables, synthesizing technical/legal/commercial findings, tracking critical issues and open items, preparing investment committee materials.

### Research & Market Analysis (15-20%)
Researching infrastructure sectors and subsectors, analyzing comparable transactions and market multiples, monitoring regulatory developments and policy changes, tracking deal flow and market activity, developing sector expertise.

### Meetings & Collaboration (10-15%)
Investment team meetings discussing active opportunities, management presentations with target asset operators, advisor meetings (technical, legal, financial), site visits to infrastructure assets, portfolio review meetings.

### Documentation & Reporting (10-15%)
Drafting investment committee papers, preparing presentation materials, writing executive summaries and key messages, documenting model assumptions and methodologies, contributing to quarterly portfolio reports.

## Workplace Culture
Fast-paced analytical environment with tight deal deadlines, collaborative team approach coordinating multiple stakeholders, intellectual rigor balanced with commercial judgment, long-term investment mindset.

